Question 23. Human fascination with animals goes back as far as humans do.

114
00:20:22,000 --> 00:20:32,000
Of the oldest cave paintings discovered, some are up to 40,000 years old and there are more images of animals than humans.

115
00:20:32,000 --> 00:20:43,000
At some point humans began to capture and hold animals. The first known collections were held by royalty and were not open to the public.

116
00:20:43,000 --> 00:20:55,000
In Egypt, researchers have found buildings from around 3500 BC containing the remains of animals including elephants which were not native to Egypt.

117
00:20:55,000 --> 00:21:04,000
But life wasn't easy for these animals. They probably had short lives and the remains show evidence of severe injuries.

118
00:21:04,000 --> 00:21:13,000
The first public exhibit of animals may have been created by Egypt's Queen Hatchepsut around 1480 BC.

119
00:21:13,000 --> 00:21:19,000
Researchers think the zoo was started with animals brought home from a far off land known as Punt.

120
00:21:19,000 --> 00:21:26,000
It's unclear why the Queen built the zoo but it might have been to show off her wealth and power.

121
00:21:26,000 --> 00:21:37,000
Early zoos are found all over the world. In China, Emperor Wenwang is said to have built a garden of intelligence around 1060 BC.

122
00:21:37,000 --> 00:21:41,000
It included deer, birds and many fish.

123
00:21:41,000 --> 00:21:53,000
In England, King Henry I set up a collection of animals in about 1110 as part of the royal estate. His collection included tigers and lions.

124
00:21:53,000 --> 00:22:03,000
This collection eventually moved to the Tower of London in 1235. The collection stayed at that location for 600 years.

